[src:io-uring/io-uring] It works by creating two circular buffers, called "queue rings", to track the submission and completion of I/O requests, respectively.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] For storage devices, these are called the submission queue (SQ) and completion queue (CQ).
[src:io-uring/io-uring] Keeping these buffers shared between the kernel and application helps to boost the I/O performance by eliminating the need to issue extra and expensive system calls to copy these buffers between the two.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] According to the io_uring design paper, the SQ buffer is writable only by consumer applications, and the CQ buffer is writable only by the kernel.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] The Linux kernel has supported asynchronous I/O since version 2.5, but it was seen as difficult to use and inefficient.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] This older API only supported certain niche use cases, notably it only enables asynchronous operation when using the O_DIRECT flag and while accessing already allocated files.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] This prevents utilizing the page cache, while also exposing the application to complex O_DIRECT semantics.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] Linux AIO also does not support sockets, so it cannot be used to multiplex network and disk I/O.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] The io_uring kernel interface was adopted in Linux kernel version 5.1 (2019) to resolve the deficiencies of Linux AIO.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] The liburing library provides an API to interact with the kernel interface easily from userspace.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] In June 2023, Google's security team reported that 60% of the exploits submitted to their bug bounty program in 2022 were exploits of io_uring vulnerabilities.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] As a result, `io_uring` was disabled for apps in Android, and disabled entirely in ChromeOS as well as Google servers.
[src:io-uring/io-uring] Docker also consequently disabled `io_uring` from their default seccomp profile.
